1. What is Git and Why Use It?
Git is a Distributed Version Control System (DVCS). Unlike older systems that required a central server to save history, Git gives every developer a full copy of the project’s history on their own machine.
Why use it?
•	Collaboration: Multiple developers can work on the "Login Page" and the "Payment Page" simultaneously without interference.
•	Version Control: If you delete a critical file by mistake, you can recover it in seconds.
•	Experimentation: You can create a "Branch," try a crazy idea, and if it fails, simply delete the branch without touching the working code.
•	Traceability: Every line of code is tagged with a name, date, and reason (the commit message).
