2. Command Deep Dive
System Configuration & Navigation
Before Git knows what to do, your computer needs to know who you are and where you are.
•	git config --global user.name "name" & user.email "mail": These settings tag your commits. Without these, Git won't let you commit because it doesn't know who to credit (or blame) for the changes.
•	git config --list: Displays all your current settings, including your name, email, and default editor.
•	mkdir <folder>: A terminal command to create a new directory (folder).
•	cd <folder>: "Change Directory." Moves your terminal's focus into a specific folder.
•	ls / ls -a: ls lists visible files. ls -a lists all files, including hidden ones like the .git folder where Git stores your history.
•	clear: Wipes the terminal screen so you have a fresh workspace.
Initializing and Cloning
•	git init: The "Big Bang" of a project. It creates a hidden .git folder. Until you run this, your folder is just a folder; after this, it is a Repository.
•	git clone "url": Downloads an entire project from a remote server (like GitHub) including all its history and branches.
The Staging Workflow
This is how you move code from your screen into Git's memory.
•	git status: Your best friend. It tells you which files are modified, which are tracked, and what is ready to be committed.
•	git add <filename>: Specifically targets one file to be moved to the "Staging Area" (the waiting room).
•	git add .: The "Add All" command. It stages every change in the current directory and subdirectories.
•	git commit -m "message": Takes everything in the Staging Area and wraps it into a permanent "Snapshot" with a descriptive label.
Remote Connections
•	git remote add origin "url": Tells your local Git repo that there is a "master copy" on a server (like GitHub) and gives it the nickname "origin."
•	git remote -v: Lists the URLs of the remote servers you are connected to so you can verify where your code is going.
•	git push origin main: Sends your local commits to the "main" branch on the remote server "origin."
•	git push -u origin main: The -u stands for "upstream." It links your local branch to the remote one so that in the future, you can just type git push without specifying the name.
Branching and Switching
•	git branch: Lists all branches in your project.
•	git branch -M main: Renames your current primary branch to "main" (this is the modern standard, replacing "master").
•	git checkout <branch>: Switches your files from the current branch to another one.
•	git checkout -b <name>: A combo command: it creates a new branch and immediately switches you into it.
•	git switch -c <name>: The modern, clearer version of checkout -b.
•	git branch -d <name>: Deletes a branch once you are finished with it (usually after merging).
