3. Advanced Operations & Undoing Changes
•	git diff <branch>: Shows the exact line-by-line differences between your current branch and another.
•	git merge <branch>: Takes the history from the specified branch and integrates it into your current branch.
•	git pull origin main: Fetches the latest code from the server and immediately tries to merge it into your local code.
•	git reset <hash>: Moves your "Time Machine" back to a specific commit. The files stay on your computer, but the "Commit" is undone.
•	git reset --hard <hash>: Dangerous. Wipes everything out and reverts your files to exactly how they were at that specific commit. You will lose unsaved work.
•	git reset HEAD~1: Undoes the very last commit and puts those changes back into your working directory.
