4. Understanding Merge Conflicts
Why do they occur?
A conflict happens when two people (or two branches) change the same line of the same file in different ways, and then try to merge them. Git is smart, but it doesn't know which version is "right." It stops the merge and asks the human to decide.
How to resolve them:
1.	Run git status: Git will tell you which files are "Unmerged."
2.	Open the file: You will see markers like this:
Plaintext
<<<<<<< HEAD (Current Change)
Blue Background
=======
Red Background
>>>>>>> feature-branch (Incoming Change)
3.	Edit: Manually delete the markers (<<<<, ====, >>>>) and keep the code you actually want.
4.	Finish: Once the file is fixed, run git add <file> and then git commit. The conflict is resolved!

